    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="264"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d264">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 E.W. 1939/10–1444</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Political Adviser, Allied Force
                        Headquarters</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 829</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caserta</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-14">October 14,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received October 25.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to transmit a brief survey<note
                        n="45" xml:id="d264fn1">Not printed.</note> made by the Combined Economic
                    Warfare Agencies attached to the Allied Force Headquarters at Caserta, which
                    discusses the economic potentialities of Rumania in the future and the ability
                    of the country to pay the reparations specified in the armistice between Rumania
                    and the Allies. The estimate is optimistic in tone and claims that Rumania by
                    devoting about half of its export surpluses over the next six years can meet the
                    reparations requirements. The study thus agrees with preliminary estimates in
                    the Department at the time of signing the armistice, <pb facs="0262" n="252"
                        xml:id="pg_252"/> that 300,000,000 United States dollars as a reparations
                    figure was not too excessive.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the United States Political Adviser: <lb/>
                    <signed>C. <hi rend="smallcaps">Offie</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Service Officer</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
